## If you must keep synchronous threads (minimal change)

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly ManualResetEventSlim _newEvent = new(false);
    private readonly Queue<string> _queue = new();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private Thread? _thread;
    private readonly object _lock = new();

    public void Start()
    {
        _thread = new Thread(RunLoop);
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop()
    {
        var handles = new[] { _newEvent.WaitHandle, _cts.Token.WaitHandle };

        while (!_cts.Token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // Blocks until either signaled OR cancelled
            int index = WaitHandle.WaitAny(handles);
            if (index == 1) break; // cancellation handle fired

            _newEvent.Reset();

            string? item = null;
            lock (_lock)
            {
                if (_queue.Count > 0)
                    item = _queue.Dequeue();
            }

            if (item is not null)
                Handle(item);
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        lock (_lock) { _queue.Enqueue(item); }
        _newEvent.Set();
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        _cts.Cancel();          // wakes WaitAny immediately
        _thread?.Join(5000);    // wait for graceful exit
        // No Abort needed — the loop checks the token and exits
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        _newEvent.Dispose();
        _cts.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* your logic */ }
}
```

---

## Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---------|---------------|
| **`Thread.Abort` → `PlatformNotSupportedException`** | Your app crashes at runtime on .NET 8, not at compile time |
| **`WaitOne()` ignores `CancellationToken`** | You must use `WaitHandle.WaitAny` with `token.WaitHandle` to make the block cancellable |
| **Race condition: multiple signals before dequeue** | Original code has this bug — `Channel<T>` or draining the queue in a loop fixes it |
| **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaks timers if you use `CancelAfter` |
| **Assuming cancellation is instant** | If `Handle(item)` takes 30s, the loop won't check the token until it finishes. Add `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` inside long handlers. |

---

## Recommendation

Use the **`Channel<T>` version** (first example). It eliminates the manual lock, the `ManualResetEvent`, and the race condition in the original code where multiple `Enqueue` calls could set the event but only one `Dequeue` fires. `Channel<T>` is the idiomatic .NET 8 producer-consumer primitive.
